From: Ichthyostega <prg@ichthyostega.de>
Date: Sat, 29 Dec 2018 05:42:17 +0100
Subject: Refactoring: extract PRNG as nested class

This changeset (hopefully) does not change any behaviour...
(with the exception of a minor adjustment on randomING() in case of #define NORANDOM )

However, hopefully it makes the code clearer by encapsulating the state.
Moreover, this refactoring simplifies experiments with various PRNG algorithms

Refactoring: simplify existing code

In the standard case, this commit again again (hopefully) changes no functionality.
The refactoring relies on knowledge about the implementation of random() and random_r()
(Based on the source code of Glibc 2.24)

 - we know that random_r(&random_buf, &random_result) can not fail (because the first arg is never NULL)
 - we know that random() rsp. random_r() return values in the range 0...INT_MAX

Simplifications
 - get rid of unneded state in the RandomGen object
 - introduce a new function prngval() for the actual random number generation
 - clarify all integer types to be explicitly 32bit
 - push out the offset on the seed values into the usage location
   (thus randomINT() gets now a more sensible contract)

*NOTE*: changed the behaviour of randomINT() #ifdef NORANDOM
In this case we now return INT_MAX/2
Basically this gives the behaviour of the former randomOG()

This minor change might break any test code written against the old NORANDOM behaviour,
but since the NORANDOM feature is new, I doubt there is any test code yet ;-)

Refactoring: move all functions into the RandomGen class body

trivial refactoring, preparation for the next step.
(Note: functions defined in a class body are automatically inline in C++)

Refactoring: disentangle the implementation

Up to now, the implementation had various intermingled conditional compilation cases,
which made reasoning about the implementation difficult.

This commit changes no functionality, but reorganises the code into a dedicated
implementation class for each of the possible PRNG implementations. The conditional
compilation is now concentrated at a single location, where we define a type alias
to the actual implementation to be used.

- in this form, it is now simple to add further implementation algorithms
- moreover, this could be the foundation to make this choice switchable from
  the instrument definition, with zero overhead (using templates)
